'''''The Dukes of Hazzard''''' is a 1984 [[Racing video game|racing]] video game developed and published by [[Coleco]] for their [[ColecoVision]] game console and [[Coleco Adam]] computer.<ref name=manual/> [[Elite Systems]] released a different game with the same title for the [[ZX Spectrum]] computer on February 23, 1985.<ref name=SSNR>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/home-computing-weekly-103/Home_Computing_Weekly_103#page/n4/mode/1up|title=Software Selection New Releases|work=Home Computing Weekly|date=March 12, 1985|accessdate=September 4, 2016|page=5}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Crash_No._14_1985-03_Newsfield_GB#page/n3/mode/2up|title=The Dukes of Hazzard (ZX Spectrum)|work=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]|date=March 1985|accessdate=September 4, 2016|page=4{{ndash}}5}}</ref> Both versions are based on [[The Dukes of Hazzard|the television series of the same name]].

[[Atari]] had previously made [[#Cancelled Atari 2600 versions|two separate attempts]] to release an [[Atari 2600]] video game based on the series, but both versions failed to materialize.

==Gameplay==
In the Coleco version, the player controls the [[General Lee (car)|General Lee]] and must drive through Hazzard County. The game's premise concerns [[Daisy Duke]], who has been abducted by Jeremiah Stinge. The player's goal is to catch Stinge, by passing his blue car, while avoiding Boss Hogg. The game ends if the player is stopped by Boss Hogg or if the player wrecks the General Lee. The game requires that the player drive at a perfect speed; driving too slow results in the player being caught by Hogg, while driving too fast can result in a vehicle collision with oncoming traffic. A rear-view mirror provides the player with a way to look out for Hogg. The player must also avoid obstacles such as oil slicks and damaged bridges. The game makes use of the ColecoVision's [[ColecoVision#Expansion Modules and accessories|Expansion Module #2 steering wheel/pedal peripheral]], and additionally requires that the player shift gears.<ref name=manual>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Dukes_of_Hazzard_The_1984_Coleco#page/n0/mode/2up|title=The Dukes of Hazzard Cartridge Instructions (Coleco)|year=1984|publisher=Coleco|access-date=August 15, 2016}}</ref><ref name=AG>{{cite web|url=http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=23266|title=The Dukes of Hazzard - Overview|last=Weiss|first=Brett Alan|work=[[AllGame]]|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141114130409/http://www.allgame.com/game.php?id=23266|archive-date=November 14, 2014|access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref><ref name=Enter/><ref name=ECN/>

The [[ZX Spectrum]] version uses a different premise: Boss Hogg threatens to seize the General Lee as [[Collateral (finance)|collateral]] unless [[Bo Duke]] and [[Luke Duke]] can provide $5,000 owed to him. Bo and Luke enter the Annual Hazzard County Cross Country Road Race, hoping to win the first-place prize of $5,000, but Hogg and the Hazzard County police attempt to halt their efforts. The game is played as a continuously scrolling roadway, with the General Lee travelling from left to right. Controlling the General Lee, the player can change lanes and speed. Enemy vehicles can be avoided or destroyed by the player using dynamite sticks. However, Daisy and her Jeep must not be destroyed. Other enemies include helicopters.<ref name=Crash1/><ref name=Crash2/><ref name=YourC/><ref name=CVG/>

==Development==
The Coleco version was announced in January 1984, at the [[Consumer Electronics Show#History|Winter Consumer Electronics Show]] in Las Vegas, Nevada.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/1984-04-compute-magazine/Compute_Issue_047_1984_Apr#page/n29/mode/1up|title=More Than 170 Programs|last=Halfhill|first=Tom R.|date=April 1984|work=[[Compute!]]|access-date=August 14, 2016|pages=26, 28}}</ref> ''The Dukes of Hazzard'' was one of only five games to utilize the ColecoVision's Expansion Module #2.<ref name=AG/> [[Lawrence Schick]] worked as a designer on the Coleco version.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://swashbucklingadventure.net/lawrence-schick/|title=Larence Schick Credits|website=SwashbucklingAdventure.net|access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref> [[Jennell Jaquays]] also worked as a designer on the Coleco version; Jaquays referred to it as one of the games that "didn't do what we had hoped," saying it was "a license we were stuck with and did what we could with it."<ref>{{cite web|url=http://opcodegames.com/coleconation/coleconation_nine.pdf|title=Coleco Chat|last=Kozlowski|first=Nathan|date=May 12, 2008|work=Coleco Nation|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=8}}</ref> The ZX Spectrum version was developed to feature nearly 100 different animated frames of the General Lee.<ref name=SSNR/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/sinclair-user-magazine-037/SinclairUser_037_Apr_1985#page/n14/mode/1up|title=Imagine that . . .|date=April 1985|work=[[Sinclair User]]|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=15}}</ref>

==Reception==
Jeff Silva of ''Expandable Computer News'', who rated the Coleco version 7 out of 10, praised the sound and graphics, and wrote that the game, "in its simplicity, captures perfectly the one-dimensional themes of the original TV show. It is difficult at first because shifting is much like shifting a manual transmission, so it takes a while to get the hang of it. The rear view mirror on the screen is a great addition." Silva concluded that the game was a "fun, though simple-minded chase through Hazzard County."<ref name=ECN>{{cite web|url=http://www.sacnews.net/adamcomputer/11.html#ECN11-12|title=Product Review: The Dukes of Hazzard|last=Silva|first=Jeff|date=November 1984|work=Expandable Computer News|access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref>

Phil Wiswell and Bernie Dekoven of [[Enter (magazine)|''Enter'' magazine]] wrote a positive review of the Coleco version: "Believe it or not, this game is good. [...]  We were worried that this game would only appeal to ''Dukes of Hazzard'' fans, and not be much fun to play. But, in fact, we think you'll like this game whether or not you care for the Duke boys and their TV show. It's a tough driving game that challenges you from start to finish." Wiswell and Dekoven called the game's rear-view mirror "a neat idea, though you don't get to use it enough."<ref name=Enter>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/enter-magazine-12/Enter_Issue_12_1984_Nov#page/n17/mode/1up/|title=The Dukes of Hazzard (Coleco)|last1=Wiswell|first1=Phil|last2=Dekoven|first2=Bernie|date=November 1984|work=[[Enter (magazine)|Enter]]|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=16}}</ref> Brett Alan Weiss of [[AllGame]] wrote that the Coleco version "is not quite on par with more traditional racers from the era such as ''[[Turbo (video game)|Turbo]]'', ''[[Pole Position (video game)|Pole Position]]'' or even ''[[Pitstop (video game)|Pitstop]]''."<ref name=AG/>

''[[Crash (magazine)|Crash magazine]]'' rated the ZX Spectrum version 63 percent and praised the graphics but criticized the gameplay.<ref name=Crash1>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Crash_No._15_1985-04_Newsfield_GB#page/n35/mode/1up/|title=Dukes of Hazzard (ZX Spectrum)|date=April 1985|work=[[Crash (magazine)|Crash]]|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=36}}</ref> ''Crash'' later wrote that "there isn't much, except the General Lee graphics, to connect the game with the TV series."<ref name=Crash2>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/Crash_No._47_1987-12_Newsfield_GB#page/n33/mode/1up/|title=Ties-Ins Part One|date=December 1987|work=Crash|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=34}}</ref> ''[[Your Computer (British magazine)|Your Computer]]'' rated the ZX Spectrum version three stars and wrote, "The screen display is excellent and the game is rather more playable than some of [[Elite Systems|Elite]]'s previous offerings."<ref name=YourC>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/your-computer-magazine-1985-05/YourComputer_1985_05#page/n44/mode/1up/|title=Dukes of Hazzard (ZX Spectrum)|date=May 1985|work=[[Your Computer (British magazine)|Your Computer]]|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=45}}</ref> ''[[Computer and Video Games]]'' said that ''Dukes of Hazzard'' fans would enjoy the ZX Spectrum version, writing that while it "isn't as spectacular as one of those amazing stunts you see the General Lee perform on TV, it ain't bad either. [...] The graphics are nice and the scrolling pretty smooth." The magazine wrote that the game can become addicting upon getting used to the controls.<ref name=CVG>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/cvg-magazine-043/CVG_043_May_1985#page/n99/mode/1up/|title=Dukes of Hazzard (ZX Spectrum)|date=May 1985|work=[[Computer and Video Games]]|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=100}}</ref>

''Home Computing Weekly'', which gave the ZX Spectrum version two stars out of five, called the game "boring", in part because of the inability to change its difficulty settings. The publication noted "the limited graphics are very well-drawn, the sound is simple but effective and machine code ensures a smooth movement of vehicles and scrolling."<ref name=HCW>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/home-computing-weekly-108/Home_Computing_Weekly_108#page/n10/mode/1up|title=The Dukes of Hazzard (ZX Spectrum)|work=Home Computing Weekly|date=April 1985|accessdate=September 4, 2016|page=11}}</ref> Three critics for ''[[Your Sinclair]]'' gave the ZX Spectrum version a negative review, criticizing the controls and poor [[collision detection]], although one reviewer felt that the game had the potential to become a commercial success.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/your-spectrum-magazine-15/YourSpectrum_15_Jun_1985#page/n55/mode/1up|title=Joystick Jury|work=Your Sinclair|date=June 1985|accessdate=September 4, 2016|pages=51, 54|quote=The score out of five at the end of each person's review is based on their experience of the game. But that's pretty subjectiveâ€¦so they also use the HIT and MISS system to indicate its potential as a commercial success.}}</ref>

==Cancelled Atari 2600 versions==
Initially, [[Atari, Inc.]] attempted to revamp the graphics of an unreleased [[Atari 2600]] port of their arcade game ''[[Stunt Cycle#Legacy|Stunt Cycle]]'', to convert it into a ''Dukes of Hazzard'' game.<ref name=Protos>{{cite web|url=http://www.atariprotos.com/2600/software/dukes/dukes.htm|title=Dukes of Hazzard (Atari 2600)|work=AtariProtos.com|access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref> For unknown reasons, Atari abandoned the idea.<ref name=Protos/> In November 1982, ''[[Atari Age (magazine)|Atari Age]]'' reported about a new video game in development at Atari that would be based on a popular [[CBS]] television series,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2600connection.com/library/magazines/atari_age/atari_age_v1n4.pdf|title=TV Hit To Hit Home Game Screens|date=November 1982|work=[[Atari Age (magazine)|Atari Age]]|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=10}}</ref> later revealed to be ''The Dukes of Hazzard'',<ref name=AtariAge>{{cite web|url=http://www.2600connection.com/library/magazines/atari_age/atari_age_v2n3.pdf|title=Game-Grams|date=September 1983|work=Atari Age|access-date=August 14, 2016|page=25}}</ref> for the Atari 2600.<ref name=Protos/>

Mark R. Hahn, the game's sole programmer, had a development team stationed in New York, while the majority of Atari's staff was based in California. Hahn claimed that the California team did not provide much assistance to his team,<ref name=Protos/> saying, "There was a lot of competition between the New York and California offices. Nobody from marketing (which was in California) was willing to tell me they didn't like the game. So I did demos of several screens, they said they liked them, and then I got working on game play."<ref name=Hahn/>

Hahn said the game was still in development in 1983, when Atari, for unknown reasons, chose to have the unfinished game burned onto a large number of [[ROM cartridge|ROM]] chips. Atari abruptly cancelled the game before the chips were to be placed into cartridges and shipped.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.2600connection.com/faq/vcs_nr/vcs_nr.html#dukes|title=The Dukes of Hazzard (Atari 2600)|work=2600Connection.com|access-date=August 14, 2016|archive-date=November 30, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161130081146/http://www.2600connection.com/faq/vcs_nr/vcs_nr.html#dukes|url-status=dead}}</ref> The game was nearly completed.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2008/05/05/beta-blues-vol-1|title=Beta Blue, Vol. 1|last=Fahs|first=Travis|date=May 5, 2008|work=[[IGN]]|access-date=August 14, 2016}}</ref> Atari was not satisfied with the game's graphics, which were lacking in comparison to other games the company was releasing at the time.<ref name=Hahn>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitpress.com/archives/interview_hahn.htm|title=Mark Hahn interview|last=Stilphen|first=Scott|date=January 16, 2005|work=DigitPress.com|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050321210045/http://www.digitpress.com/archives/interview_hahn.htm|archive-date=March 21, 2005}}</ref> Hahn only learned of the game's cancellation from the secretary of an Atari VIP, and said, "I had put months of very long days and weekends into the game. I was a bit upset."<ref name=Hahn/> ''Atari Age'' reported the game's cancellation in September 1983.<ref name=AtariAge/>

The game would have had the player control the General Lee, with the goal being to break Daisy out of jail before Boss Hogg can get to her, while also avoiding [[Sheriff Rosco P. Coltrane]] and [[The Dukes of Hazzard#Main characters|Deputy Enos Strate]] in their police vehicles. The game contained many glitches and gameplay issues. One of the game's major glitches included Rosco and Enos abruptly ramming the General Lee if it got too close to their vehicles, resulting in the player losing a life.<ref name=Protos/>

